        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "External reranker",
        "body": "## Summary\r\n\r\nWhat problem does this PR solve?\r\nOpenClaw's memory-core has no support for external rerankers whe using memorySearch:query:hybrid — only the built-in MMR algorithm or switching the entire system to QMD. QMD is local-only, so the reranker runs on the gateway. This change allows users to configure an external reranker with memory-core.\r\n\r\nWhy does this matter now?\r\nIt increases the quality of results from memory searches. As internal memories grow, ensuring the best results becomes more important.\r\n\r\nWhat is the intended outcome?\r\nBetter results from memory searches.\r\n\r\nWhat is intentionally out of scope?\r\nQMD, LanceDB, and other memory systems for Openclaw.\r\n\r\nWhat does success look like?\r\nSubtle, but important, the user doesn't notice any difference other than \"Openclaw is better at finding information in memories\".\r\n\r\nWhat should reviewers focus on?\r\nLook at the interface used between memory-core and MMR. MMR has been moved to a plugin, and the new external reranker uses the same interface.\r\n<details>\r\n<summary>Summary guidance</summary>\r\n\r\nThis PR makes two changes. First, it moves mmr to a bundled plugin called memory-mmr. Second, it adds a memory-external-reranker plugin to memory-core, enabling external reranker support for Cohere-compatible /v1/rerank endpoints. \r\n\r\nIt is designed so that users with existing memorySearch:query:hybrid configuruations see no difference and don't have to update their configuration to continue to use the existing mmr. Only when the user enables and memory-external-reranker plugin and adds the other necessary config entries will the external reranker be used.\r\n\r\nit's also designed so the user can configure mmr as a fallback if the external reranker fails for any reason (plugin not loaded, external reranker call fails).\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n## Linked context\r\n\r\nWhich issue does this close?\r\n\r\nCloses #64438\r\n\r\nWhich issues, PRs, or discussions are related?\r\n\r\nRelated #\r\n\r\nWas this requested by a maintainer or owner?\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<summary>Linked context guidance</summary>\r\nhttps://github.com/openclaw/openclaw/issues/64438\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n## Real behavior proof (required for external PRs)\r\n\r\n- Behavior or issue addressed: external reranker called during memory recall\r\n- Evidence after fix (screenshot, recording, terminal capture, console output, redacted runtime log, linked artifact, or copied live output):\r\n\r\nLogs from a running OpenClaw instance showing the external reranker in action:\r\n\r\n```\r\n13:09:30+00:00 debug [memory-external-reranker] reranking with provider=local-llm-server-02-8082 model=mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0 fallbacks=none topN=30 documents=34\r\n13:09:30+00:00 debug [memory-external-reranker] candidate=local-llm-server-02-8082/mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0 model=mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0 url=http://local-llm-server-02:8082/v1/rerank topN=30 documents=34\r\n```\r\n...\r\n```\r\n13:09:36+00:00 debug [memory-external-reranker] candidate=local-llm-server-02-8082/mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0 response status=200 ok=true\r\n13:09:36+00:00 debug [memory-external-reranker] candidate=local-llm-server-02-8082/mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0 success: 30 documents reranked\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe reranker plugin loaded as a gateway plugin, received 34 candidate documents, sent them to the remote endpoint, and returned 30 reranked results.\r\n\r\n- Observed result after fix: better search results from memory\r\n- What was not tested: QMD, LanceDB, other memory systems\r\n- Proof limitations or environment constraints:\r\n- Before evidence (optional but encouraged):\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<summary>Real behavior proof guidance</summary>\r\n\r\nconfig json fragments\r\n\r\nagents:defaults:\r\n```\r\n      \"memorySearch\": {\r\n        \"enabled\": true,\r\n        \"provider\": \"openai-compatible\",\r\n        \"model\": \"Qwen/Qwen3-Embedding-4B-GGUF:Q8_0\",\r\n        \"query\": {\r\n          \"hybrid\": {\r\n            \"enabled\": true,\r\n            \"vectorWeight\": 0.7,\r\n            \"textWeight\": 0.3,\r\n            \"mmr\": {\r\n              \"enabled\": true,\r\n              \"lambda\": 0.7,\r\n              \"provider\": \"memory-external-reranker\",\r\n              \"fallback\": \"memory-mmr\"\r\n            }\r\n          }\r\n        },\r\n        \"remote\": {\r\n          \"baseUrl\": \"http://local-llm-server-02:8081/v1\",\r\n          \"apiKey\": {\r\n            \"source\": \"env\",\r\n            \"provider\": \"default\",\r\n            \"id\": \"LOCAL_LLM_02_KEY\"\r\n          },\r\n          \"batch\": {\r\n            \"enabled\": false\r\n          },\r\n          \"nonBatchConcurrency\": 3\r\n        },\r\n      }\r\n\r\n```\r\nmodels:providers:\r\n```\r\n      \"local-llm-server-02-8082\": {\r\n        \"baseUrl\": \"http://local-llm-server-02:8082\",\r\n        \"models\": [\r\n          {\r\n            \"id\": \"mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0\",\r\n            \"name\": \"mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0\",\r\n            \"input\": [\r\n              \"text\"\r\n            ]\r\n          }\r\n        ]\r\n      }\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nplugins:entries:\r\n```\r\n      \"memory-external-reranker\": {\r\n        \"enabled\": true,\r\n        \"config\": {\r\n          \"provider\": \"local-llm-server-02-8082\",\r\n          \"model\": \"mradermacher/Qwen3-Reranker-4B-GGUF:Q8_0\",\r\n          \"topN\": 30\r\n        }\r\n      },\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\n- Real environment tested: multiple test VMs. I've been running it on my production Openclaw instance for over a week.\r\n- Exact steps or command run after this patch: Enable and configure the memory-external-reranker plugin, index memory, perform a memory search like \"What do you remember about the Lucid Air?\" See attached screenshot.\r\n<img width=\"1836\" height=\"1578\" alt=\"full-rerank-image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/fdfc712d-6662-4bc4-b8c4-827d289be454\" />\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n## Tests and validation\r\n\r\nWhich commands did you run?\r\npnpm build && pnpm check && pnpm test\r\npnpm test:extension memory-external-reranker\r\npnpm test:extension memory-mmr \r\n\r\nWhat regression coverage was added or updated?\r\nFull tests added for both MMR plugin and new external reranker plugin.\r\n\r\nWhat failed before this fix, if known?\r\n\r\nIf no test was added, why not?\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<summary>Testing guidance</summary>\r\n\r\nTo do full testing, an embedding model and reranking model are needed. I use llamacpp on localhost and update openclaw.json to point to the local models.\r\n```\r\n./llama-server -hf Qwen/Qwen3-Embedding-0.6B-GGUF --port 8081 --embedding\r\n./llama-server -hf ggml-org/Qwen3-Reranker-0.6B-Q8_0-GGUF --port 8082 --embedding --reranking --pooling rank\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n## Risk checklist\r\n\r\nDid user-visible behavior change? No\r\n\r\nDid config, environment, or migration behavior change? Yes. New config entries added\r\n\r\nDid security, auth, secrets, network, or tool execution behavior change? No. Uses existing patterns and code to call external reranker.\r\n\r\nWhat is the highest-risk area?\r\nMemory search results are not reranked by either the external reranker nor MMR.\r\n\r\nHow is that risk mitigated?\r\nMMR is a bundled plugin. As long as mmr is a buldled plugin and loaded by default, the risk is minimal.\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<summary>Risk guidance</summary>\r\n\r\nMinimal risk once MMR is a bundled plugin.\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n\r\n## Current review state\r\n\r\nWhat is the next action?\r\n\r\nWhat is still waiting on author, maintainer, CI, or external proof?\r\n\r\nWhich bot or reviewer comments were addressed?\r\n\r\n<details>\r\n<summary>Review state guidance</summary>\r\n\r\nKeep this as the durable state for review progress. If useful information appears in comments, fold the current next action or blocker back here so maintainers and ClawSweeper do not need to reconstruct state from comment history.\r\n\r\n</details>\r\n",
